@startuml DailyProblemClassification_SP_Complete
title CTS_DC_CustClassification_DailyScanPA_Complete - Detailed Flow

skinparam backgroundColor #FFFFFF
skinparam handwritten false
skinparam noteBackgroundColor #FFF9C4
skinparam noteBorderColor #FBC02D
skinparam activityBackgroundColor #F3E5F5
skinparam activityBorderColor #7B1FA2

start

:Stored Procedure Called;
note right
  **SP Name**: CTS_DC_CustClassification_DailyScanPA_Complete
  **Database**: CTS_DataCenter.ctsServiceAdmin (MySQL)
  **Timeout**: 300 seconds (default)
  **Parameters**: @CustIDs (comma-separated string)
  **Called From**: PADailyScanCompleteCriteria
end note

:Receive CustIDs Parameter;
note right
  **Input Parameter**: @CustIDs (string)
  
  **Format**: Comma-separated list
  **Example**: "123456,789012,345678,901234"
  
  **Source**: 
  - Processed customers from current batch
  - Extracted from PADailyScanFromQueueModel
  - JOIN with comma delimiter
  
  **Usage**:
  - Mark these customers as processed
  - Remove from queue
  - Prevent re-processing
end note

if (CustIDs is NULL or empty?) then (yes)
  :Log Warning;
  note right
    **Warning**: No CustIDs provided
    - Possible empty queue
    - Or processing error
    - Skip deletion
  end note
  :Return without action;
  stop
else (no)
endif

:Parse CustID string to list;
note right
  **String Parsing**:
  - Split by comma delimiter
  - Trim whitespace
  - Convert to numeric list
  - Validate format
  
  **MySQL Method**:
  - FIND_IN_SET() function
  - Or temp table with split
  - Or JSON_TABLE if formatted as JSON
  
  **Result**: Array of CustIDs
end note

:Create temp table #CustIDsToDelete;
note right
  **Temp Table**:
  - CustID (long)
  - One row per customer
  - Used for JOIN with queue table
  
  **Purpose**:
  - Efficient batch deletion
  - Avoid string parsing in WHERE clause
  - Better query performance
end note

:Validate CustIDs exist in queue;
note right
  **Validation Query**:
  SELECT COUNT(*) 
  FROM CTSCustomerClassification_DailyPAQueue q
  INNER JOIN #CustIDsToDelete t ON q.CustID = t.CustID
  
  **Purpose**:
  - Ensure customers are in queue
  - Detect orphaned CustIDs
  - Log discrepancies
end note

:BEGIN TRANSACTION;
note right
  **Transaction Management**:
  - Ensure atomicity
  - All-or-nothing deletion
  - Rollback on error
  - Maintain data consistency
end note

partition "Delete from Queue" {
  :Execute DELETE statement;
  note right
    **DELETE Query**:
    DELETE FROM CTSCustomerClassification_DailyPAQueue
    WHERE CustID IN (SELECT CustID FROM #CustIDsToDelete)
    
    **Effect**:
    - Remove processed customers from queue
    - Free up queue space
    - Enable next batch processing
    
    **Indexed on CustID** for performance
  end note

  :Get affected rows count;
  note right
    **Row Count**:
    - Number of customers deleted
    - Should match input CustID count
    - Discrepancy indicates issue
  end note
}

if (Deletion successful?) then (yes)
  :COMMIT TRANSACTION;
  note right
    **Commit Success**:
    - Changes persisted
    - Queue cleaned
    - Ready for next batch
  end note
  
  :Log Success;
  note right
    **Success Logging**:
    - Customer count deleted
    - Execution time
    - Queue size remaining
  end note
else (no)
  :ROLLBACK TRANSACTION;
  note right
    **Rollback**:
    - Undo all changes
    - Queue unchanged
    - Customers remain for retry
  end note
  
  :Log Error;
  note right
    **Error Logging**:
    - Error message
    - CustIDs that failed
    - Stack trace
    - Alert for investigation
  end note
  
  :Throw Exception;
  stop
endif

:Check remaining queue size;
note right
  **Queue Size Check**:
  SELECT COUNT(*) 
  FROM CTSCustomerClassification_DailyPAQueue
  
  **Purpose**:
  - Determine if more customers to process
  - Return isContinue flag
  - Drive recursive processing
  
  **Logic**:
  - Count > 0 → isContinue = true
  - Count = 0 → isContinue = false
end note

if (More customers in queue?) then (yes)
  :Return isContinue = true;
  note right
    **More to Process**:
    - Queue not empty
    - Recursive call triggered
    - Next batch will be fetched
    - JobRun() called again
  end note
else (no)
  :Return isContinue = false;
  note right
    **Queue Empty**:
    - All customers processed
    - Job completion
    - No recursive call
    - Wait for next job trigger
  end note
endif

:Update statistics;
note right
  **Statistics Update**:
  - Total processed today
  - Average processing time
  - Queue throughput
  - Performance metrics
end note

:Cleanup temp table;
note right
  **Cleanup**:
  - DROP temp table #CustIDsToDelete
  - Release resources
  - Memory cleanup
end note

stop

note bottom
  **Queue Management**:
  
  **Purpose**: Mark PA customers as processed and remove from queue
  **Effect**: Enables FIFO processing for next batch
  **Transaction**: Ensures data consistency
  
  **Queue Lifecycle**:
  1. **Insert**: RealtimeClassification adds PA customers
  2. **Fetch**: GetFromQueue retrieves oldest customers (FIFO)
  3. **Process**: DailyProblemClassification processes batch
  4. **Complete**: This SP deletes processed customers
  5. **Repeat**: Until queue empty
  
  **Error Handling**:
  - Failed processing: Customers remain in queue
  - Automatic retry on next job run
  - Transaction rollback on error
  - Alert if queue grows too large
  
  **Performance Optimization**:
  - Batch deletion (not one-by-one)
  - Indexed deletion (CustID index)
  - Transaction batching
  - Temp table for efficiency
  
  **Monitoring**:
  - Queue size tracking
  - Processing rate monitoring
  - Average processing time
  - Alert thresholds:
    * Queue size > 100,000
    * Processing time > 1 hour
    * Error rate > 5%
  
  **Recursive Processing Logic**:
  ```
  do {
    customers = GetFromQueue()
    if (customers.Any()) {
      Process(customers)
      UpdateComplete(customers)
    }
    isContinue = (queue.Count > 0)
  } while (isContinue)
  ```
  
  **Table Cleanup**:
  - Regular deletion prevents table growth
  - Maintains FIFO performance
  - Prevents index fragmentation
  - Optimizes query execution
end note

@enduml

